In Go, you have a running Workflow that executes ActivityA, and you want to replace it with ActivityC without causing nondeterminism errors. You deploy the following patched code:

```go
v := workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step1", workflow.DefaultVersion, 1)
if v == workflow.DefaultVersion {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityA, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
} else {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityC, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
}
```

What does `workflow.GetVersion()` record in the Event History for a brand-new Workflow Execution that runs this code for the first time?

A team is running long-lived Go Workflows (some 6+ months old) on a Task Queue. They introduce a change: replace `ActivityA` with `ActivityC`. They use `workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step1", workflow.DefaultVersion, 1)` and deploy. Three months later, all pre-patch Workflow Executions have finished retention. They update the code to:

```go
v := workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step1", 1, 2)
if v == 1 {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityC, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
} else {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityD, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
}
```

They also have Workflows still running that were started when `maxSupported` was 1 (i.e., they recorded version 1 in history). What happens when those version-1 Workflows replay against this new code?
